elper might be inaccessible due to it being private. If I want to leverage macro support, I’ll need both the actor and reflect libraries. I’m wondering if generated tests can provide meaningful coverage without additional dependencies since the jar only contains internal macros. The POM indicates that actor and scala-reflect are provided, yet the existing test already includes both, leading me to think that deterministic dependencies are likely needed, so I'll have to check version compatibility.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test-code guidance**\\n\\nI think I should mention some test-code guidance regarding the ccompat pre213/since213 classes that were removed in version 2.0.0-M1. It's important to avoid using those and focus instead on org.apache.pekko.macros.LogHelper and LogHelperMacro. Plus, I need to take into account that there's private[pekko] visibility. So, should I recommend using reflection or ensuring proper package placement for testing? It feels critical to guide users in the right direction.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Scala dependencies**\\n\\nI need to consider that scala-reflect should match the compiler version. It seems like I should use tck.scala2Version instead of a fixed version. The user is asking for just an extra Maven dependency, but the build may already include scala-compiler and scala-library from tck. Adding scala-reflect version 2.13.18 alongside compiler 2.13.17 might cause a conflict. I really need to check the tck.scala2Version property, as it might need to be updated to 2.13.17.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_xttZZzGVwsmkQleNMcGopkwd|fc_0f4608fd4b9620e3016a42b31371a08190bb6ddcc476a71cfa", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"scala2Version|2\\.13\\.17|2\\.13\\.18\" -n build.gradle gradle.properties tests buildSrc tck-build-logic 2>/dev/null | head -80", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1